        "id": "49f5a54f-4116-4353-9f5d-4092a955ddb0",
        "score": 0.64739007,
        "text": "This document page provides an analysis of the SPP (Southwest Power Pool) market footprint, focusing on net revenue by resource zone and installed capacity within the SPP.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Market Signals and Generation Retirement**: The market signals the retirement of inefficient generation due to aging fleets and increased environmental restrictions. These factors may raise the resource margin, making higher net revenue price signals more important. The Integrated Marketplace's ability to provide these incentives and long-term price signals is highlighted as a significant benefit.\n\n2. **Net Revenue Analysis by Zone (Figure 2-7)**: The table presents net revenue data ($/MW Year) for three types of generation resources\u2014Scrubbed Coal, Gas/Oil Combined Cycle, and Combustion Turbine\u2014across six resource zones (AEP, KCPL, NPPD, OGE, SPS, WR). It also indicates whether each resource type in each zone can recover all costs or avoidable costs. Key observations:\n   - None of the resource types in any zone can recover all costs.\n   - All resource types in all zones can recover avoidable costs.\n   - Scrubbed Coal has the highest net revenue values, followed by Gas/Oil Combined Cycle, then Combustion Turbine.\n\n3. **Capacity in SPP (Section 2.3)**:\n   - **Installed Capacity (Section 2.3.1)**: The Integrated Marketplace's installed generating capacity for the SPP Consolidated Balancing Authority is shown for the launch date (March 1, 2014) and one year later (March 1, 2015).\n   - Total generating capacity increased by about 1.5% to 75,458 MW over the first year.\n   - Natural gas holds the largest market share at 47%, with coal second at 35%.\n   - Changes in capacity are partly due to existing capacity, often owned by municipal utilities, registering to participate directly in the market rather than behind the meter. This capacity is mostly older and small units.\n   - Retirements, mainly of very small older coal units, also contributed to changes.\n   - Wind capacity continues to grow due to new construction.\n\nOverall, the page discusses the financial viability of different generation types across zones, the importance of market signals for resource management, and recent trends in installed capacity within the SPP market.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2014/page_30.jpg",
          "page_num": 30,
          "title": "2014 State of the Market",
          "year": 2014,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "fd82f52f-4659-463d-a322-7146a8636b92",
        "score": 0.6462113,
        "text": "This document page from the \"SPP 2012 State of the Market Report\" by Southwest Power Pool, Inc. discusses the categorization and generation of power resources based on their operational status.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- Definitions of resource statuses:\n  - Resources in \"Up and Testing\" status cannot set prices and are dispatched at their last known output.\n  - \"Self-scheduled\" resources are dispatched based on predetermined schedules by Market Participants, independent of market conditions.\n  - \"Unavailable\" status means the resource is offline and not available for market use.\n  - \"Supplemental\" status indicates the resource is offline but can come online within ten minutes.\n\n- Generation by Status:\n  - Figure II.22 shows generation from resources in various status types.\n  - Market available resources generated about 80% of total generation in 2011, similar to previous years.\n  - There has been a steady decline in Self-Dispatched generation, indicating increased confidence by Market Participants in the EIS Market's ability to dispatch resources.\n  - There is a notable reduction in the use of manual status (startup, shutdown, testing), which increases resource availability for dispatch.\n  - Intermittent resources are becoming more common in the EIS Market, contributing a larger share of total generation.\n\n- The figure includes two charts:\n  - A monthly bar chart for 2011 and 2012 showing generation in GWh by status type (Market Dispatch, Self-Dispatch, Nuclear, Intermittent, Manual).\n  - A stacked bar chart from 2008 to 2012 showing the percentage share of generation by status type, highlighting the dominance of Market Dispatch and the decline of Self-Dispatch over time.\n\nOverall, the page highlights trends in resource dispatching, increased market confidence, and the growing role of intermittent resources in the energy market.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2012/page_66.jpg",
          "page_num": 66,
          "title": "2012 State of the Market",
          "year": 2012,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c1e0702e-ee51-4839-9663-4b551858ed4e",
        "score": 0.6411712,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. discusses the utilization of different status types for market resources and their impact on market operations.\n\n**Status Type Utilization:**\n- Market Participants can modify resource control parameters by selecting a status type in their resource plans, which dictates how the resource functions.\n- In 2010, there were five status types: available, unavailable, self-scheduled, manual, and supplemental.\n- In late February 2011, the \"manual\" status was discontinued and replaced with several new types: exigent conditions, intermittent, qualifying facility, quick start, shut down, start up, and testing.\n- Only the \"available\" status allows full market utilization of a resource, enabling it to adjust output and set system prices.\n- \"Manual\" status indicates uncontrollable resources that cannot set prices and are dispatched at their last known output.\n- Self-scheduled resources operate based on predetermined output levels regardless of market conditions.\n- \"Unavailable\" status means the resource is offline and not usable by the market or participant.\n- \"Supplemental\" status means the resource is offline but can come online within ten minutes.\n- Available status units are most valuable to the market as they can respond quickly to instructions, helping resolve congestion and operational constraints.\n\n**Generation by Status Type:**\n- Most generation comes from market-available resources, allowing efficient operation and resolution of constraints.\n- The \"Start-up, Shut-down, and Test\" category was introduced in February 2011.\n- Intermittent resources are gaining importance in the EIS Market, with status types separated to categorize generation properly.\n- There is a noted steady decline in self-dispatched generation.\n\nOverall, the page explains how different resource status types affect market participation, resource dispatch, and generation efficiency, highlighting changes made in 2011 to improve categorization and market operation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2011/page_65.jpg",
          "page_num": 65,
          "title": "2011 State of the Market",
          "year": 2011,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1da7136f-85c6-4de4-a99c-fba080cf9880",
        "score": 0.6312902,
        "text": "This document page from Southwest Power Pool, Inc.'s Market Monitoring Unit (MMU) presents an analysis to determine if the SPP market supports investments in new power generation technologies. The analysis compares fixed costs, annual fixed operating and maintenance costs, and potential net revenues of five generation technologies at SPP market prices. The technologies evaluated are scrubbed coal, natural gas combined-cycle, natural gas combustion turbine, wind, and solar photovoltaic tracking.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. Cost Assumptions:\n   - Solar capital costs are adjusted for investment tax incentives.\n   - A capital recovery factor of 12.6% is applied to annual fixed operating and maintenance costs.\n   - Table (Figure 4-46) details assumptions for each technology, including size (MW), total overnight cost ($/kW-yr), variable and fixed operating and maintenance costs ($/MWh and $/kW-yr), and heat rate (Btu/kWh).\n   - For example, scrubbed coal has the highest total overnight cost ($5,716/kW-yr) and heat rate (9,257 Btu/kWh), while combined-cycle natural gas has lower costs and heat rate.\n\n2. Net Revenue Analysis:\n   - The analysis assumes market dispatches the resource when day-ahead prices exceed short-run marginal production costs.\n   - Natural gas prices are based on the Panhandle Eastern Pipeline Company (PEPL) pipeline.\n   - Wind is assigned a 39% capacity factor across all hours, and solar a 49% capacity factor during peak hours.\n   - Wind's average marginal cost is credited for production tax incentives.\n\nThe page concludes that the net revenue analysis results are shown in a subsequent figure (4-47), with footnotes clarifying that net revenue equals revenues minus estimated marginal cost and that real-time prices yield similar results.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2019/page_196.jpg",
          "page_num": 196,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET 2019",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ad291b99-dc50-4c07-bd4f-79e3f0b7cb6a",
        "score": 0.62803936,
        "text": "This page is from a report by the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit, focusing on market prices and costs. It briefly mentions the importance of pricing products and capacity ratings to align reliability and economics in the power generation market. The effectiveness of this pricing will influence future price signals for investment in the SPP market. It also notes that this topic is discussed in more detail in Section 7 of the report. The page is from the \"State of the Market 2021\" report and is numbered 198.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_212.jpg",
          "page_num": 212,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "186afab0-3754-4e7c-a897-1c6c0f9e01df",
        "score": 0.62748396,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit report discusses the trends and analysis of electricity generation by technology type within the SPP Integrated Marketplace.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- Interconnection requests for solar generation increased significantly, more than fourfold from 2016 to 2017, with over 1,000 MW of requests for combined solar farm and battery storage sites in 2017. Battery-only interconnection requests remain minimal.\n- The development of renewable generation, particularly wind and solar, is expected to continue in the SPP region. Proper integration of these renewable sources is essential for maintaining system reliability.\n- Section 2.4 focuses on generation by technology, emphasizing the importance of analyzing generation types to understand pricing, environmental impacts, regulatory requirements, and market dynamics such as congestion management, price volatility, and market efficiency.\n- Figure 2-19 (included on the page) shows annual generation percentages by technology type in the SPP real-time market from 2007 to 2017. The graph illustrates a decline in coal generation and a rise in wind generation over this period, with other technologies like gas (simple and combined cycle), hydro, and nuclear remaining relatively stable.\n\nOverall, the page highlights the shift in the energy mix within the SPP market, with increasing renewable energy integration and the implications for market operations and reliability.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2017/page_46.jpg",
          "page_num": 46,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a3fd538d-caab-43f9-8d69-86a260313fdd",
        "score": 0.620562,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit discusses the distribution of 89 resource owners registered to participate in the Integrated Marketplace as of December 31, 2021. It includes a pie chart (Figure 2-2) illustrating the breakdown of resource owners by type:\n\n- Independent power producers: 56\n- Investor-owned utilities: 8\n- Cooperatives: 7\n- Municipal: 6\n- Marketer: 6\n- State agency: 3\n- Industrial: 1\n- Federal agency: 1\n- Agent: 1\n\nThe text explains that the high number of independent power producers is largely due to the inclusion of most wind producers in this category. The term \"agent\" refers to several individual resource owners who would otherwise be classified under different types such as municipal utilities, electric cooperatives, and state agencies.\n\nAdditionally, the document notes that Figure 2-3 (not shown on this page) presents the generation nameplate capacity owned by each type of market participant. It highlights that investor-owned utilities and cooperatives together own 54 percent of the nameplate generation capacity in the SPP market.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_42.jpg",
          "page_num": 42,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "493d06b1-88ef-41de-b893-aee41ecd7fba",
        "score": 0.6117188,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit discusses the analysis of new generation investments in the SPP market. It outlines reasons for new generation investments, including corporate renewable goals, out-of-market payments, bilateral contracts, purchase power agreements, market protocol requirements, federal/state incentives, state-regulated investments, emerging technologies, and emission reduction plans.\n\nThe Market Monitoring Unit (MMU) conducted an analysis to determine if the SPP market supports investments in new generation by comparing fixed costs and annual fixed operating and maintenance costs of five generation technologies\u2014scrubbed coal, natural gas combined-cycle, natural gas combustion turbine, wind, and solar photovoltaic with storage\u2014against their potential net revenues at SPP market prices. The analysis uses daily averages and assumptions to estimate profitability for constructing new generation and ongoing costs but does not reflect profitability of existing generators or include costs like supply adequacy penalties and individual contracts.\n\nThe analysis is described as high-level, relying on several assumptions and averages. Gas prices were taken as daily averages at a single gas hub per region, excluding bilateral trades or additional charges. Energy prices were also daily unweighted averages. Due to volatile gas and energy prices during the February weather event, some assumptions and averages may not be reliable for long-term investment decisions.\n\nFinally, the page notes that Figure 4\u201343 provides cost assumptions for a new generator, with a capital recovery factor of 12.6% used in the annual fixed operating and maintenance cost component. A footnote clarifies that net revenue equals revenues minus estimated marginal cost.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_206.jpg",
          "page_num": 206,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "77e9529d-2cf3-4144-8e1c-341ae6c47236",
        "score": 0.60727483,
        "text": "This document page from the \"SPP 2013 State of the Market Report\" discusses the dispatch and generation status of resources within the Southwest Power Pool (SPP) market.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- **Dispatch of Self-Scheduled Resources:** These resources are dispatched based on the sum of their schedules, with market participants pre-determining output levels regardless of market conditions. Dispatch levels can be adjusted by the RTO Reliability desk through the TLR schedule curtailment process.\n- **Resource Status Definitions:**\n  - *Unavailable status* means the resource is offline and not available for use by the market or participant.\n  - *Supplemental status* means the resource is offline but can come online within ten minutes.\n- **Generation Trends by Status Type:** \n  - Figure II.23 shows generation from resources by status type.\n  - Market available resource generation decreased slightly from 80% in 2012 to about 77% in 2013.\n  - Use of manual statuses (startup, shutdown, exigent conditions, testing) and self-scheduled status remained low.\n  - Intermittent status usage increased significantly from 8.6% in 2012 to 11.5% in 2013, attributed to growth in wind resources in SPP.\n  \nThe figure includes two charts: a monthly generation bar chart for 2012-2013 broken down by status types (Market Dispatch, Self-Dispatch, Nuclear, Intermittent, Manual) and a stacked bar chart showing the percentage generation by status type from 2007 to 2013, highlighting the increase in intermittent generation over time.\n\nOverall, the page highlights the operational status and dispatch patterns of resources in the SPP market, emphasizing the growing role of intermittent resources like wind power.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2013/page_63.jpg",
          "page_num": 63,
          "title": "2013 State of the Market",
          "year": 2013,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "5df4160c-5cce-47d4-9894-3117aa9ad10d",
        "score": 0.60604167,
        "text": "This page from the document provides an overview of the electricity supply in the SPP (Southwest Power Pool) market, focusing on generation by technology type.\n\n1. **Figure 2-20**: The figure presents three line graphs comparing yearly degree days and system loads from 2013 to 2015 against a normal year:\n   - **Heating Degree Days**: Shows monthly heating degree days for 2013, 2014, 2015, and a normal year. The values peak in winter months (January, December) and are lowest in summer.\n   - **Cooling Degree Days**: Shows monthly cooling degree days for the same years, peaking in summer months (June, July, August).\n   - **SPP System Load**: Displays the monthly system load in GWh for 2013, 2014, 2015, and a normal year. The load peaks in summer (July) and has a secondary peak in winter (December, January).\n\n2. **Section 2.5 - Electricity Supply in the SPP Market**:\n   - **2.5.1 Generation by Technology Type**: This section discusses the importance of analyzing generation by technology type in the SPP Integrated Marketplace. Understanding the types of generation helps in pricing, assessing environmental and regulatory impacts, and understanding market dynamics such as congestion management, price volatility, and overall market efficiency.\n   - It mentions that Figure 2-21 (not shown on this page) depicts annual generation percentages by technology type from 2007 to 2015.\n   - A key point is that generation from simple cycle gas units (gas turbines and gas steam turbines) has significantly declined over recent years.\n\nOverall, the page combines graphical data on weather-related demand indicators and system load with a textual analysis of generation technology trends in the SPP market, highlighting shifts in generation sources and their implications for market operations.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2015/page_37.jpg",
          "page_num": 37,
          "title": "2015 State of the Market",
          "year": 2015,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

