        "score": 0.60604167,
        "text": "This page from the document provides an overview of the electricity supply in the SPP (Southwest Power Pool) market, focusing on generation by technology type.\n\n1. **Figure 2-20**: The figure presents three line graphs comparing yearly degree days and system loads from 2013 to 2015 against a normal year:\n   - **Heating Degree Days**: Shows monthly heating degree days for 2013, 2014, 2015, and a normal year. The values peak in winter months (January, December) and are lowest in summer.\n   - **Cooling Degree Days**: Shows monthly cooling degree days for the same years, peaking in summer months (June, July, August).\n   - **SPP System Load**: Displays the monthly system load in GWh for 2013, 2014, 2015, and a normal year. The load peaks in summer (July) and has a secondary peak in winter (December, January).\n\n2. **Section 2.5 - Electricity Supply in the SPP Market**:\n   - **2.5.1 Generation by Technology Type**: This section discusses the importance of analyzing generation by technology type in the SPP Integrated Marketplace. Understanding the types of generation helps in pricing, assessing environmental and regulatory impacts, and understanding market dynamics such as congestion management, price volatility, and overall market efficiency.\n   - It mentions that Figure 2-21 (not shown on this page) depicts annual generation percentages by technology type from 2007 to 2015.\n   - A key point is that generation from simple cycle gas units (gas turbines and gas steam turbines) has significantly declined over recent years.\n\nOverall, the page combines graphical data on weather-related demand indicators and system load with a textual analysis of generation technology trends in the SPP market, highlighting shifts in generation sources and their implications for market operations.",
